The difference between a mediocre action film and a great one is as much about form as content. A great action sequence is a lot like a great piece of music. It‚Äôs about pace and the right rhythm of tension and catharsis.
.
I think this brief moment of wirework In Non-Stop is very cool. It immediately made me think of Max Payne. In those games, you can enter slow-motion gun-fu dives that last as long as ten seconds. It‚Äôs incredibly satisfying. The long gun dives in Max Payne and The Matrix are so effective because of how they manipulate pace. They are long gorgeous drawn-out notes that when done right make a moment that combines tension and beauty to create awe. Just like in the wrenching musical notes of the violins of Barber‚Äôs Adagio for Strings or Wagner‚Äôs Tristan and Isolde, drawwwinnnggg out the moment infuses it with power.
.
I think there was a great, and much longer shot of this dive. A version that if used differently could have made this shootout famous. But instead, its chop, chop, chopped into a shakycam montage mess.
.
You can see the misaimed style in the grading too. The sterile look of most plane interiors is part of the claustrophobic nature of flying. That could have been embraced and played with. Last year I saw Chris Nolan‚Äôs ‚Äúunrestored‚Äù cut of 2001. It was amazing to see Space Odyssey in theaters, but the ‚Äúunrestored‚Äù digital scan had a major color shift in it. The age of the negatives turned the whites into ‚Äúwarm white.‚Äù Nolan‚Äôs intent was to show the original 2001. But it wasn‚Äôt really the original. The yellows had dampened the tension of the iconic sterile spaceship whites. You can see the sterility of the ungraded airplane set of Non-Stop in the BTS footage. I find the ungraded color to be more evocative than the grade.
.
For some reason, arbitrary genre conventions were chosen instead of the footage‚Äôs natural feel. This is yet another example of why DPs should be incorporated into post. The DP can be there to represent the footage as it was intended on set. And so provide balance against the cookie-cutter disease that seems to infect post-production these days.

He would often take people with missing limbs or other disabilities into the arena, tie them together, and club them to death. Spike Jonze's Apple commercial is quite famous, and I bumped into it again yesterday and found myself thinking about the thought process of something so practical effects heavy. So here are the pros and cons of approaching such a concept with practical effects.

The pros:
1 - The camera is free to move without concerns of motion tracking digital effects.
2 - Talent is able to react to the spectacle of the effects in real time.
3 - ¬†Post-production time is substantially diminished.
4 - Less interference is possible from the client due to reduced time and importance of post.
5 - Practical effects are harder to imitate without hiring the original crew who made them.
6 - The practical effects are inherently more timeless and unique due to their real-world imperfections.
7- Iteration and adaptation of the concept are easier due to a tighter loop of feedback.
8 - The more basic effects (like telescoping of the table and papers) are simply easier as practical effects than VFX.
9 - You have more fun on set.
10 - You have better bragging rights.

The cons:
1 - You‚Äôre forced to obey the laws of physics.
2 - Specialists with the necessary expertise are harder to find and more localized than their post-production counterparts.
3 - Practical effects necessitate a larger and better-organized crew.
4 - The risk of major setbacks is higher due to a greater concentration of time, people, energy and money on set in principle photography.
5 - You‚Äôre more locked into the final look of the effect.
6 - Total cost is probably higher.
The most compelling point within this list is pros #5. The simple sad fact is that if you execute a fantastic digital effect chances are you will be imitated by other people trying to replicate it for cheaper. But, if it‚Äôs all practical effects you stand a higher chance of getting the call to repeat your own work from new clients. Clients tend to see VFX as a magic trick, and practical effects as true magic.

Episode 7 of @euphoria required a lot of teamwork, timing, and a little movie magic. 
This is a great example of the collaborative process. In order to achieve the in camera effect of Rue being in multiple places at once  all departments had to come up with creative ways to tackle the shot. Timing was essential with everyone working together, making adjustments from take to take until you capture something magical.
